During start up, Confluence wipes the {{plugins-cache}} directory and writes all user installed plugins from the {{plugindata}} table to the {{plugins-cache}} directory on disk. This can cause slowness during start up when there are a lot of user installed plugins or when the size of the user installed plugins is very large.

Ideally Confluence should check to see which plugins are already cached to disk and skip rewriting those plugins unless they have been updated.

